Soon after returning from South America, Kligler left the Rockefeller Institute and the USA for Palestine, arriving in 'Eretz Israel' in early 1921 as part of the [[Third Aliyah]]. However, he retained working contacts with the Rockefeller Foundation, and in 1926, before joining the Hebrew University in Jerusalem, he took part in a yellow fever mission organized by the Rockefeller Foundation to West Africa.<ref>{{cite journal
