In 1922 Kligler gave the first course in aspects of hygiene at the Hadassah Hospital in Jerusalem. The course was given in Hebrew. Four of the  five participants in the first course joined him at the  "Anti-Malaria Research Institute" that opened in September 1922 in Haifa 
as anti-malaria inspectors.

In early 1930's the Hebrew University began teaching courses in the natural sciences. During Kligler's tenure, more than forty students completed their studies in a master's degree and doctorate in natural sciences in the Department of Microbiology.<ref>{{cite journal| last = Olitzki| first = L.| last2 = | first2 = | date = 1944| title = In memoriam of Israel Kligler| url = | journal = Harefuah| publisher = Israeli Medical Association| volume = 27| issue = | pages = 189-185| doi = | accessdate =}}</ref> 
